description.text:
After more than a year of challenging myself using different extruders’ topologies and feed screws, from the learned lessons, I propose a new geometry that takes into account the weak points and the desire of printing with elastomers. The new extruder features are: simple to print and assemble, easy to use and to clean, capable to print with various kinds of materials including highly elastic ones. Besides, it has a potential of further development and a flexible model of the system that is possible to change. Therefore it is useful to change the nozzle diameter to sufficiently increase the speed; or to attach the filament sensor to control the fusion. The extruder was tested with E3D V6 normal hotend an Volcano, giving very good results.
The printing of spare parts is pretty easy. We use PLA. Note that main_body and idler must be printed in 100% infill. extruder_holder and sensor_holder are good with 50% infill. Remove the support material with stationary knife and file the holes to loosen them if needed. Do not forget to cut the PTFE tube properly (it is around 75 degrees angle) and insert it from down up. This is the key part on your way to print with elastomers.
Use mk8 and any stepper motor you prefer (we use NEMA17).
You can print E3D V6 Groove mount or order one. Up to you.
See assembly video: https://youtu.be/8maw2MqtUZU
Also there is a full assembly stl, not to print, but to see what is what.

Feel free to post your makes and remixes. Let me know if any of the models' files are damaged.

title: Sony Action Cam pistol grip mount

description.text:
Hi All,
i wanted a comfy grip mount for my sony action cam for surf/water shooting. i used a model of a pistol grip and added a mount for the camera I attach a fishing trace to the camera and run it down the hole in the centre of the grip and attached it to a fin saver that straps to my wrist. Worst case I let go of the camera and the mount breaks everything will be still attached to me. It works out to be a comfortable position of the start stop button to use your thumb. Fasteners/extra parts required: (all 316SS if using in ocean)
  • 1/4" x 3/4" UNC hex bolt (STD camera mount, cut down to suit, could possibly use a 1/2")
  • M6 x 30 button head cap screw
  • M6 nyloc nut
  • A fin saver (loops around the M6 bolt, straps to your wrist) or any kind of wrist strap.
  • 50lb fishing trace (min 200 long, one end attached to the camera the other to the fin saver)
    • Please note i had some troubles with the export of the knob part and it was coming out a random scale, let me know if this is still a problem and I will try and fix it.

• Print parts (I used an UP Mini 3D, printed the camera mount and knob as solid parts and used the fine honeycomb fill setting for the grip.)
  • Cut the 1/4" UNC bolt down to the correct length (ensure it does not hit the camera housing on the inside)
  • press the bolt into the knob part
  • Glue the camera mount to pistol grip part (make sure the knob is in place before you do this)
  • Cut the M6 x 30 bold down to suit and screw into the hole at the bottom of the grip (make sure you do not over tighten and crush the grip part, especially if printed hollow)
    • Enjoy

Here is a customizable version of a Chanukah dreidel (top toy). I made these for my nieces and nephews for Chanukah. Unfortunately, two of my nieces had names longer than 4 letters, so I created a non-traditional 6-sided dreidel.'
Using Blender, I customized each side to spell-out names.

Open the Blender file and edit it. Add text to write whatever you want. Convert the text to a mesh, and "extrude" it to create a 3D object. Export the various parts (except the stem) to an STL file and print it.
Separately, print the stem STL and insert it into the dreidel. You may need to drill or file a little to make it fit. You may want to use a little super glue as well.

The brackets secure to the studs in your wall with 2 screws each. I believe the screws I used were #8 screws, 1 1/2" long. They barely fit through the holes, so anything wider probably wouldn't work. If you need me to make the screw holes bigger just ask me and I'll do it for you. You could also just use a drill bit to make the holes bigger if you need to.

I printed at 50% infill and my 50 foot cord is putting a good amount of pressure on the brackets and bending them, so I would advise to do around 75% infill or even 100, but you can get away with 50% as long as you're careful not to wrap the cords too tightly around the brackets.

Hi!

Due the nice response from the communty with LiBu, a printed mini laser engraver structure, we proudly present BiBu, your BIG Burner!

BiBu, as its little sister, is a laser engraver engraver structure, the initial idea was a fully 3D printed structure, but in many ways, to 3D print a big structure is virtually imposible taking in consideration that it must be precise and sturdy.

To fight that, we did chose an Open Hardware aluminium profile to make the long structure parts, V-Slot, because there are many printable parts out there, and the smooth linear motion that features is well balanced with the price and availability, also, there's a an awesome community around the product and derivatives

Then we found this on the nets, while searching for a V-Slot distributor:

  • http://openbuilds.org/?category=laser-cutter-builds&id=304

A whole world of information, an incredibly clever pinion/belt systems ideas, this makes the engraver able to work on walls and non-horizontal surfaces, based on V-Slot, and with a huge work on information about the electronics. So we took the site as a base to make our "fully 3D printable" big laser engraver.

Check the site, an amazing work that worth the study.

Finally we closed the design using:
//// HARDWARE ////

  • 3 NEMA 17 motors
  • 4 x 50cm 2020 V-Slot aluminium profile *1
  • 1 x 47cm 2020 V-Slot aluminium profile
  • 3 x GT2 Aluminium pulley
  • 4 x 55cm GT2 Belt
  • 12 x V-Slot Delrin mini v wheel Kit *2
  • N x M3x12

//// 3D PRINTED ////

  • 2 x Y-StepperCarry
  • 1 x laser_StepperPlate_X
  • 2 x axis_spacer_X_HolderV5
  • 6 x V-slot-belt_end
  • 1 x laser_support
  • 4 x upper_corner
  • 4 x bottom_corner *3
  • N x V-Slot Nuts

All printed parts have a slight clearance on the sizes and diameters (about 0.2mm), specially thinking in FDM users.

*1: To cut costs, you may use standard aluminium extrusion (cheaper) in the sides that are not involved with the linear motion, but remember that the nuts are diferent.

*2: There are some methods to cut costs in this mini v wheel parts, using 3D printed rollers for motion (not tested, and adds extra screws/spacers/... that come with the miniwheel kit)

*3: Our prototype bottom corner is designed for enclose 4 x printer rubber rollers, extracted from an old printer, to act as supports, but the bottom corner is extracted from the upper one, so there are many options to make proper supports just adding a few walls.

For electronics, we used a cheap laser engraver controller board, thore are sold in many sites nowadays.

As always, this project is deeply inspired by the work of other people who likes to make things, We'll try to list them all, forgive us if we miss someone:

For the projects that made us dream with big lasers. Actually you triggered the LiBu project. :)

For their accurate work in traducing the Open Source hardware to cheap and easy to print parts

There are many other alternative rollers to replace the mini wheels, but we stumbled upon this ones.

And many many more that we can't remember, thanks too :)

REMEMBER THAT A LASER MAY SERIOUSLY AND DEFINITIVE HARM YOUR EYES, DO NOT EVEN START THE LASER PARTS IF YOU DIDN'T GOT A GOOD PAIR OF GOOGLES, AND REMEMBER THAT THEY HAVE TO BE SPECIAL FOR YOUR LASER COLOR (WAVELENGTH). description.text:
I liked the A1 new corner idea quite a bit - but I hated the thought of having to drill in and get a metal shim. I also hated the idea of needing to raise the glass. This removes that need!   
So what I did instead is develop a shim from the outside. I had alot of 3mm screws that the A1 used, but I bought a box of 100 screws (M3 -0.50 x 20 m) and 100 nuts of them from Amazon ($5 each), which you may need. Now you still tighten the corners as described by the previous version (not too tight?) but you can raise and lower each corner of the bed using an external screw and only plastic!  
The other good part is if you do see some plastic fatigue because you run your bed much hotter, you just print another. Quick change! But I doubt you'll need to.   
This also eliminates metal from touching the kapton heat spreader or the glass.  
Let me know what you guys think, this is my first design to be functional and my first contribution to Thingiverse!   
PS, You do need to rotate the each piece before printing, and yes the pieces do clear the smooth rods.

This model is my first attempt to create an Aurora-class Starfury (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starfury) from the television show Babylon 5. I've always liked the design of this one-man fighter craft and decided that it would be a fun and challenging design project. The included STL files were designed for efficiency of printing and assembling a single model. You can use the included OpenSCAD files to print individual parts or make modifications. I hope to make the OpenSCAD files easier to modify at some point. Although this is a pretty good first attempt, there are several features that are not quite correct.
  • The upper supports are much simpler than they should be.
  • The forward guns are not as well-formed and sturdy as I would like.
  • The detail on the sides of the body could use some work.
  • The back of the model has no detail at all.
    • As my design skills improve, I hope to revisit this model. UPDATE: The instructions have been improved and the extra thruster nozzles have been removed from the engines4 model.

The model is made up of a number of pieces that must be glued together to make the final piece. I used an ABS/acetone mixture as glue. I assume superglue or model cement would work as well. You need to print one each of
  • stand.stl - support for model
  • body.stl - main body
  • struts.stl - connect the engines to the body
  • engines4.stl - mount at the ends of the struts
  • thrusters.stl - small thruster engines at right angles to main engines
  • baffles_all.stl - baffles mounting to the rear of the main engines
    • Note: The body (body.stl) has four conical supports that snap off after the print is complete. Sometimes these will disconnect when you remove the body from the build platform. That is not a sign of a problem. If any of the supports remain attached to the body, they should snap off relatively easily. Note: Almost all parts should be relatively insensitive to minor differences in printer configuration. However, I found that the baffles_all.stl only prints well with extra shells set to 0 and 100% infill (in the Fill plugin).

  • (stand.stl) Glue the flat part of the cross shape on top of the shaft, inserting the pin on the top of the shaft in the hole on the top.

  • Glue the wide portion of one pair of struts (struts.stl) to the upper support on the body (body.stl). The flat portion of the struts will be on the bottom. Both the side of the strut and the mount point are angled, so the result should angle upward. (Look at the pictures to determine which part of the body is the top.)
    • If necessary, sand off any rough spots to allow for a good fit. You will need to hold or tape this piece in place until the glue dries.
  • Glue the wide portion of the other pair of struts to the supports on the lower sides of the body. The flat portion of the struts should face up. Both the side of the strut and the mount point are angled, so the result should angle downward. If necessary, sand off any rough spots to allow for a good fit.
    • You will need to hold or tape this piece in place until the glue dries.
  • Now is a good time to attach (not glue) the body to the stand. This will make further work easier, since there is no flat portion of the model that you can set down. The longer portion of the top of the stand should match with the front of the model.
    • There are two pair of rectangular supports on the bottom of the body. These supports should match the gaps in the side rails of the top of the stand. A little pressure should friction-fit these pieces together.

  • Each of the engines (engines4.stl) has a pair of holes at right angles on the side of the engine. These are mounting points for the little thruster nozzles (thrusters.stl). Glue one nozzle with the shaft inside each of the two side holes on the engine. Repeat for each of the four.

  • There are two different versions of the engine (engines4.stl). Find the engine that matches with the top right strut (looking at the small end, the thrusters will point up and right and the engine mount will be on the top left).
    • Glue the engine mount to the end of the top right strut. If necessary, sand off any rough spots to allow for a good fit. You will need to hold or tape this piece in place until the glue dries.

  • Find the engine that matches the top left strut (thrusters point up and left, engine mount on top right). Glue the engine mount to the end of the top left strut. If necessary, sand off any rough spots to allow for a good fit.

  • Find the engine that matches the lower right strut (thrusters point down and right, engine mount on lower left). Glue the engine mount to the end of the lower right strut. If necessary, sand off any rough spots to allow for a good fit.

  • Find the engine that matches the lower left strut (thrusters point down and left, engine mount on lower right). Glue the engine mount to the end of the lower left strut. If necessary, sand off any rough spots to allow for a good fit.

  • The baffles (baffles_all.stl) require some minor modification before mounting. With the flat side down, there are two grooves that run lengthwise down each baffle. The sides of the baffle should be bent upward about 10-15 degrees on each side.

  • Each of the little fingers at the end of the baffle also need to be bent slightly upwards (maybe 5 degrees).

  • Repeat steps 10 and 11 for all 8 baffles.

  • The smaller baffles mount on the side of the rear nozzle closest to the body. There is a small hole that matches a small pin on the top front of the baffle. (It is relatively close to the angle of the support strut.)
    • Glue this pin in the hole. You will need to hold this for some time until the glue sets. Try to keep the fingers pointed directly to the rear of the module.

  • Repeat step 13 for all of the small baffles.

  • The larger baffles mount on the outside of the rear nozzle. There is a small hole that matches a small pin on the top front of the baffle. (It is very close to directly opposite the angle of the support strut.)
    • Glue this pin in the hole. You will need to hold this for some time until the glue sets. Try to keep the fingers pointed directly to the rear of the module.
  • Repeat step 15 for the rest of the large baffles.
    • Congratulations, you have your own Starfury model!

author: bdwalker1

title: Remix of Optical Illusion Pinwheel with Thicker Blades

description.text:
This is a remix of Dalpec's very cool Optical Illusion Pinwheel. This remix fixed a print problem I had with Dalpek's original blade stl files. The blades got too thin near the ends and would not print (see photo). These are close to the originals but not exact. I also did two versions. On the arc versions the blades get taller (thicker?) in the middle. I didn't like the way they printed because of the steps in the slight curve so I did another version that is basically flat.

I also remixed the handle. This version is cut in half and prints flat on the bed. Not as cool because you need to print two and glue them together. It will fit without rotation on a Mini bed but I would recommend rotating it 45 degrees on the bed anyway. That keeps the ends closer to the middle of the bed where it is hotter. I printed one square and at the end near the edge of the bed the print lifted a little. It also has a revised clipless retention system. Print the washers from Dalpek's original Thing. They should just snap onto the handle to hold the wheel.

Edit 5-10-16:
I had a request for some modified blades that might spin with less wind. I added some blades with thicker blade sections (.375 & .5) and one with a flatter pitch that should give more revs for a given wind speed. Although for the cool visual effect that Dalpek's original has I prefer a slower rotation.

title: Recycle calibration boxes into 15 tiles game

description.text: After giving kids another pile of 20mm calibration boxes and seeing complete lack of interest in the eyes, it struck me that the boxes can be used as tiles for a puzzle game I saw a long time ago. The only thing it needs is a box and 15 tiles with numbers. The tiles are mixed at the start and the goal is to arrange them in order by sliding into the only free spot available (without taking out of the box). P.S. If you want to make a nice print of this puzzle rather than find a way to reuse a pile of the calibration boxes take a look at the thing already available on the Thingiverse: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15377

The design file for the box is attached. You'll need fifteen 20mm calibration boxes for the tiles and a way to write the numbers on them (Sharpie worked for me). Print the box, put the tiles in and you are done. The lid is a slide-in. The box dimensions are 88x88mm.

title: Scalar - Adjustable Inductive probe support for AllInOne Hot End Support

description.text:
This Thing is an upgrade to the existing AllInOne support for Scalar 3D Printers ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:967021 )

It allows to adjust the Inductor probe manually using a screw driver.

How to proceed:

  • Place the nozzle of your hotend so that it touches the heatbed
  • Move the hot end up of about 0.2 or 0.3mm
  • Set your ZOffset to 0.2 or 0.3mm => save your settings
  • Turn right or left the adjustment screw so that the led indicator on the probe is switched on.

Now you should be set!
